(120, '2009-05-19', 87, 1, 6, 'River Otter', '', 'central-park-zoo/river-otter', 'Central Park River Otter - CentralPark.com', '<p>The northwest corner of the Central Park Zoo&rsquo;s Temperate Zone is home to two \r\n<table border="0" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center">\r\n<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center"><img src="http://www.centralpark.com/pages//zoo/otter[1].jpg" border="0" alt="River Otter at the Central Park Zoo" width="200" height="148" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="right"><a href="http://www.maryschwalm.com/" target="_blank"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><em>Mary Schwalm</em> </span></a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center">\r\n<p align="left"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><strong>River Otter in a pensive mood <br />at the Central Park Zoo.</strong> </span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\nNorth American river otters (Lutra Canadensis): Erin and Olgi. This species is crepuscular (active at dawn and dusk) so the best time to see them is when just after the zoo opens or before the zoo closes.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Exhibit</strong> : A small pool filled with 5 gallons of water and 40 inches deep. The area is surrounded by land and by trees, including Red twig dogwood and Arrow-wood viburnum.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Habitat</strong> : North America from Florida to Alaska. North American river otters are not necessarily confined to rivers, as their name implies. They may be found near rivers, streams, swamps, marshes, bays, ponds, lakes, and even near sea coasts. A male&rsquo;s range may be 60 square miles, while a female&rsquo;s range may vary from 12 square miles to 30 square miles depending on the age of her young and the availability of a second family car.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Diet</strong> : In the CPZ, Erin and Olgi are fed horsemeat, kale, and carrots. As a treat they will occasionally get live fish in their pool to hunt and eat. In the wild, river otters may eat small fish such as mud minnows and other marine life such as eels, crayfish, crabs, frogs, snakes, turtles, insects, mollusks, birds, and small mammals.</p>\r\n<p>Otters are adept hunters and their bodies are made for movement on land and in the water. They are able to close their nostrils and ears under water, and may dive to depths up to 35 feet. Using their clawed, webbed feet and long tails to propel and steer themselves, they may reach speeds up to 7 miles per hour. Amazingly, by alternating steps and belly slides a North American river otter can move along on land up to 15-18 mph. Sight and touch are important and their whiskers are sensitive to water turbulence, which helps them locate movement in the water. Their water-repellent fur helps them stay warm along with the dense under fur so they can stay warm in and out of the water, even at the northernmost part of their territory- Alaska.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Life span</strong> : In the wild river otters may live up to 16 years. In captivity, they may live up to 23 years.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Threats </strong>: Hunted for pelts, over trapping, and human development: wetland drainage and damming.</p>', 'The northwest corner of the Central Park ZooÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s Temperate Zone is home to two North American river otters (Lutra Canadensis): Erin and Olgi. ', 'Central Park, NYC, New York City, weekend, weekend actvities, North American River Otter, Central Park Zoo', 56.90, 14, '<script type=''text/javascript''><!--//<![CDATA[\r\n   var m3_u = (location.protocol==''https:''?''https://ads.centralpark.com/www/delivery/ajs.php'':''http://ads.centralpark.com/www/delivery/ajs.php'');\r\n   var m3_r = Math.floor(Math.random()*99999999999);\r\n   if (!document.MAX_used) document.MAX_used = '','';\r\n   document.write ("<scr"+"ipt type=''text/javascript'' src=''"+m3_u);\r\n   document.write ("?zo