(166, '2009-06-14', 145, 2, 14, 'John B. Moore', '', 'about-centralpark-com/staff/john-b-moore', 'John B. Moore - CentralPark.com Staff', '<p>John first came to New York City on a class trip senior year in High School. <img src="http://www.centralpark.com/pages//about/johnny.jpg" border="0" alt="Johnny B. Moore" hspace="5" vspace="5" width="185" height="200" align="right" />He immediately wandered off and became blissfully lost. A few years later, after a cross-country journey to find himself (or at least someone that looked good in his clothes) he moved to Manhattan and discovered Central Park. He realized that this was by far the best place in the City to get lost. Since that time he has worked in New York as a bartender, freelance writer and web designer.</p>\r\n<p>About seven years ago the original designers of CentralPark.org (Jay and Liana Fayloga) moved to the west coast and passed over the management of the site to John. He has operated the site ever since, enjoying his duties answering the questions of school children around the world and updating schedules. Now, thanks to the vision of child prodigy <a href="page.php?pid=144">Aric Boyles</a>, he is able to devote his passion for Central Park to a much more ambitious project as Content Director for CentralPark.com.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Blog - <a href="http://www.centralparkblogger.com">CentralParkBlogger</a> - News and Views on the word''s most famous public space.</p>\r\n<p>Writing Portfolio - <a href="http:www.lostinnewyork.com">Lost In New York</a></p>\r\n<p>Follow John on <a href="http://www.facebook.com/profile.php?id=1214736285&amp;ref=profile">Facebook</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Important facts:</p>\r\n<li>He read the entire works of Edgar Rice Burroughs and Arthur Conan Doyle by the age of 12. </li>\r\n<li>He loves jazz, but doesn''t pretend to know a lot about it. </li>\r\n<li>He thinks "The Pope of Greenwich Village" is the best bad movie ever made. </li>\r\n<li>His favorite author is John Hawkes. </li>\r\n<li>He once closed his eyes at an Eagles concert and realized that Timothy B. Schmidt sounds exactly like Anne Murray. It changed his life. </li>\r\n<li>He has never offered to show himself out. </li>\r\n<li>He finds talking about himself in the third person more than a little bit tedious. </li>', 'CentralPark.com - John B. Moore - Raconteur - Automath - ', 'Central Park, NYC, New York City, ballfields, Balto, baseball, basketball, Belvedere Castle, Bethesda Fountain, Bethesda Terrace, bike, Boathouse, Bow Bridge, Calvert Vaux, Carousel, Central Park Conservancy, Central Park History, children, climbing wall, conservancy, family programs, Frederick Law Olmsted, Frederick Olmsted, Gates, Great Lawn, Greensward, Harlem Meer, Heckscher ballfields, Ice Skating, Imagine, Lasker Rink, Loeb Boathouse, merry-go-round, Metropolitan Museum, Obelisk, Olmsted, park, playground, public monuments, public park, Ramble, recreation programs, reservoir, rock climbing, row boating, running track, Sheep Meadow, skating, softball, Strawberry Fields, Tavern on the Green, tennis, tennis court, tours, Vaux, volunteer, volunteer programs, walking tours, wall climbing, weekend, weekend actvities, weekend family programs, Wollman Rink, Central Park Zoo', 89.80, 87, '', '', '', '', 'bow_bridge.jpg', '<a href="http://www.centralpark.com/pages/about-centralpark-com/staff/rick-anderson.html">Rick Anderson</a>', '', '', 0, '', '', 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 'John B. Moore', 'John B. Moore', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00');
