(186, '2013-10-24', 2, 1, 15, 'Cherry Hill', '', 'attractions/cherry-hill', 'Cherry Hill in Central Park', '<table style="background: #ffffff; margin: 0 0 3px 5px;" border="0" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" align="right">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center">\r\n<table style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% #ffffff; width: 200px;" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="right">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center"><a title="Cherry Hill Horse and Concourse" rel="lightbox-guide" href="http://www.centralpark.com/updata/Image/attractions/cherry-hill-horse-and-concourse-f.jpg"></a> <img src="http://www.centralpark.com/updata/Image/attractions/cherry-hill.jpg" border="0" alt="Cherry Hill" width="200" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style="font-size: xx-small;" align="right"><strong>Cherry Hill Horse and Concourse</strong> by <em><a href="http://www.centralpark.com/members/profile30076.html" target="_blank">Jay_Singer</a></em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>Overlooking the Lake lies the peaceful Cherry Hill, located at 72nd street.  Though the Hill itself was named for the beautiful cherry blossom trees that bloom there during the springtime, the area is most noted for its 14-foot fountain.</p>\r\n<p>The Cherry Hill Fountain, first unveiled in 1860, was originally designed to function as a watering trough for horses.  Though no horses drink from the Fountain today, they and their carriages still frequent the area, available for park-goers who wish to take a scenic drive in one of these old-fashioned vehicles.  The Fountain was designed by Jacob Wrey Mould, the designer of the Bethesda Fountain, which lies to the west.  The Cherry Hill Fountain can be recognized by its decorative glass lamps and globes.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0 0 20px; text-align: right;"><small>&mdash; Jesse M. Wheeler </small></p>\r\n{{ADSPACE_300_250}}', 'Though the Hill itself was named for the beautiful cherry blossom trees that bloom there during the springtime, the area is most noted for its 14-foot fountain.', 'Cherry Hill, cherry blossom, spring time, Cherry Hill Fountain', 76.80, 19, '<script type=''text/javascript''><!--//<![CDATA[\r\n   var m3_u = (location.protocol==''https:''?''https://ads.centralpark.com/www/delivery/ajs.php'':''http://ads.centralpark.com/www/delivery/ajs.php'');\r\n   var m3_r = Math.floor(Math.random()*99999999999);\r\n   if (!document.MAX_used) document.MAX_used = '','';\r\n   document.write ("<scr"+"ipt type=''text/javascript'' src=''"+m3_u);\r\n   document.write ("?zoneid=15&blockcampaign=1");\r\n   document.write (''&cb='' + m3_r);\r\n   if (document.MAX_used != '','') document.write ("&exclude=" + document.MAX_used);\r\n   document.write ("&loc=" + escape(window.location));\r\n   if (document.referrer) document.write ("&referer=" + escape(document.referrer));\r\n   if (document.context) document.write ("&context=" + escape(document.context));\r\n   if (document.mmm_fo) document.write ("&mmm_fo=1");\r\n   document.write ("''></scr"+"ipt>");\r\n//]]>--></script><noscript><a href=''http://ads.centralpark.com/www/delivery/ck.php?n=a026fe8a&cb=INSERT_RANDOM_NUMBER_HERE'' target=''_blank''><img src=''http://ads.centralpark.com/www/delivery/avw.php?zoneid=15&n=a026fe8a'' border=''0'' alt='''' /></a></noscript>', '', '', '', 'lake800.jpg', '<a href="http://www.centralpark.com/pages/about-centralpark-com/staff/aric-boyles.html">Aric Boyles</a>', '', '', 0, '', '', 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 'Cherry Hill', 'Cherry Hill', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(187, '2009-05-15', 17, 1, 14, 'Walking Tour 1', '', 'maps/walking-tour-1', 'Walking Tour through Central Park', '<p>The first of our walking tours will begin at the north end of the <a href="page.php?pid=51" target="_blank">Mall</a>, \r\n<table border="0" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center">\r\n<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center"><img src="http://www.centralpark.com/pages//attractions/mall3.jpg" border="0" alt="The Mall in Central Park" width="200" height="150" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="right"><a href="http://centralparkblogger.com/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><em>John B. Moore</em> </span></a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center">\r\n<p align="left"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><strong>The Mall in Central Park.</strong> </span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\nextend south down along the Promenade to the <a href="page.php?pid=51" target="_blank">Literary Walk</a> and then to the <a href="page.php?pid=39" target="_blank">Carousel</a>. From the Carousel we go south again past the <a href="page.php?pid=30" target="_blank">Chess and Checkers House</a>, <a href="page.php?pid=86" target="_blank">Wollman Rink</a>, around the <a href="page.php?pid=188" target="_blank">Hallett Nature Sanctuary</a>, finally finishing at the <a href="page.php?pid=74" target="_blank">Pond</a>.</p>\r\n<p>Designed by Vaux and Olmsted as a &ldquo;grand promenade&rdquo; the Mall joins with <a href="../../page.php?pid=37">Bethesda Terrace</a>, both geographically and stylistically, to fulfill the park&rsquo;s need for a place that offered visitors a chance to socialize; an alternative to the secluded paths and solitary walks that populate so much of the terrain. The forty foot wide Mall, flanked by its majestic rows of American Elms, provides the perfect place for a leisurely stroll in any season, especially the fall. One can easily imagine the scene a century ago, women with parasols and men in top hats perambulating towards the Concert Ground that stood adjacent to its northern end. On the left is the historic Naumberg Bandshell. Built in 1923 it has been the stage for concerts by an eclectic array of artists, from John Philip Sousa to the Grateful Dead, and it is still the home of an annual series of summer concerts.</p>\r\n<p>Walking south beneath the cathedral-like canopy brings us to an area known as the Literary Walk that is populated with a series of sculptures depicting popular figures in world literature and music. Personalities represented include Shakespeare, Victor Herbert, Robert Burns and Ludwig van Beethoven, as well as Sir Walter Scott. The end of the Promenade brings us to the park Drive which we follow down and to the right which brings us to The Carousel.</p>\r\n<p>The Central Park Carousel opened in 1871 and was powered by a blind mule and a horse which walked a treadmill in an underground pit. It almost immediately became one of the park&rsquo;s most popular attractions and remains so to this day, with almost 250,000 riders a year. Visitors will want to check out the wrought iron fence that surrounds the open Carousel sides; small, brightly-painted horses are depicted on a band around the fence. The Carousel is open seven days a week, weather permitting, and for $1.25 you can climb aboard for an exciting three-and-a-half minute ride.</p>\r\n<p><center style="page-break-after: always;"></center></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>From the Carousel we walk southeast past the Chess and Checkers House. Built in 1952 as a gift of philanthropist Bernard Baruch, the octagonal red and cream colored brick structure has indoor as well as outdoor tables that attract play&shy;ers of all ages and prowess. A pergola offers plenty of shade. Continuing on we pass Wollman Skating Rink built in 1949 it has been a success from the day it opened - over 300,000 skaters glided across the ice in its first year of operation and in the summer it is the home of the Victorian Gardens Amusement Park.</p>\r\n<p>Walking south and then west from the rink we pass the Hallett Nature Preserve to our right. Originally set aside as a bird sanctuary in 1934 this four acre plot of land is bounded on three sides by the Pond and is only yards away from the bustle of Central Park South and the Plaza Hotel some fifty feet above. It is the permanent and transitory home of dozens of species of birds as well as rabbits, raccoons and even woodchucks. Continuing past the Preserve brings us to the final stop on our virtual tour &mdash; Gapstow Bridge and the Pond.  <br /> <br />Gapstow Bridge is a lovely construct of stone that stretches gracefully over the north end of the Pond and offers one of the most picturesque views in all of Manhattan. Looking out over the bucolic splendor of the Pond, with its gently curving shoreline and overhanging trees our gaze is drawn upwards to the manmade spectacle above, the New York skyline extending over Grand Army Plaza. The Pond is most remarkable for being so close to the clamor of the city, yet thanks to the brilliance of the landscape design by Frederick Law Olmsted and Calvert Vaux, it is completely removed into a world all its own. A few short feet from Fifth Ave. a park visitor can easily imagine themselves somewhere in the Catskills, far from the gasp and clatter of the metropolis above.  <br /> <br /><a href="http://www.centralparkbb.com/tour_1.htm" target="_blank">Printable Map of Tour 1</a></p>', 'CentralPark.com - Your first stop for information on Central Park and The Central Park Zoo!  Including extensive event listings, maps, attractions, sports, activities, history, essential info for tourists.', 'Central Park, NYC, New York City, ballfields, Balto, baseball, basketball, Belvedere Castle, Bethesda Fountain, Bethesda Terrace, bike, Boathouse, Bow Bridge, Calvert Vaux, Carousel, Central Park Conservancy, Central Park History, children, climbing wall, conservancy, family programs, Frederick Law Olmsted, Frederick Olmsted, Gates, Great Lawn, Greensward, Harlem Meer, Heckscher ballfields, Ice Skating, Imagine, Lasker Rink, Loeb Boathouse, merry-go-round, Metropolitan Museum, Obelisk, Olmsted, park, playground, public monuments, public park, Ramble, recreation programs, reservoir, rock climbing, row boating, running track, Sheep Meadow, skating, softball, Strawberry Fields, Tavern on the Green, tennis, tennis court, tours, Vaux, volunteer, volunteer programs, walking tours, wall climbing, weekend, weekend actvities, weekend family programs, Wollman Rink, Central Park Zoo', 4.50, 3, '', '', '', '', 'sheep_meadow.jpg', '<a href="http://www.centralpark.com/pages/about-centralpark-com/staff/rick-anderson.html">Rick Anderson</a>', '', '', 0, '', '', 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 'Walking Tour 1', 'Walking Tour 1', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(188, '2013-10-24', 2, 1, 15, 'Hallett Nature Sanctuary', '', 'attractions/hallett-nature-sanctuary', 'Hallett Nature Sanctuary in Central Park', '<table style="margin: 0 0 3px 5px;" border="0" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center">\r\n<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center"><a title="Hallett Nature Sanctuary" rel="lightbox-guide" href="http://www.centralpark.com/updata/Image/attractions/hallett-nature-sanctuary-f.jpg"> <img style="border: 0pt none;" src="http://www.centralpark.com/updata/Image/attractions/hallett-nature-sanctuary.jpg" alt="Hallett Nature Sanctuary" width="200" /> </a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center">\r\n<p align="right"><span style="font-size: xx-small;"><strong>Hallett Nature Sanctuary</strong>, by <a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/jag9889/">Mario Burger</a></span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>Hallett Nature Sanctuary is a four-acre nature preserve that is located just northwest of the Pond at 5th Avenue and Central Park South.</p>\r\n<p>Restored in the 1980''s, Hallett Nature Sanctuary was first declared a bird sanctuary in 1934, and has remained so ever since.  There are in fact many different animal species in addition to the Santuary&rsquo;s bird population, including raccoons, rabbits, and woodchucks.</p>\r\n<p>Visitors may not be allowed in the Sanctuary by themselves, but half-hour guided tours are held at certain times throughout the year.  These tours educate visitors about the various types of wildlife that inhabit the preserve, including the large number of migratory birds that frequent the Sanctuary.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0 0 20px; text-align: right;"><small>&mdash; Jesse M. Wheeler </small></p>\r\n{{ADSPACE_300_250}}', 'Hallett Nature Sanctuary is a four-acre nature preserve that is located just northwest of the Pond at 5th Avenue and Central Park South.', 'Hallett Sanctuary, pond, nature sanctuary, raccoons, birds, rabbits', 4.00, 2, '<script type=''text/javascript''><!--//<![CDATA[\r\n   var m3_u = (location.protocol==''https:''?''https://ads.centralpark.com/www/delivery/ajs.php'':''http://ads.centralpark.com/www/delivery/ajs.php'');\r\n   var m3_r = Math.floor(Math.random()*99999999999);\r\n   if (!document.MAX_used) document.MAX_used = '','';\r\n   document.write ("<scr"+"ipt type=''text/javascript'' src=''"+m3_u);\r\n   document.write ("?zoneid=15&blockcampaign=1");\r\n   document.write (''&cb='' + m3_r);\r\n   if (document.MAX_used != '','') document.write ("&exclude=" + document.MAX_used);\r\n   document.write ("&loc=" + escape(window.location));\r\n   if (document.referrer) document.write ("&referer=" + escape(document.referrer));\r\n   if (document.context) document.write ("&context=" + escape(document.context));\r\n   if (document.mmm_fo) document.write ("&mmm_fo=1");\r\n   document.write ("''></scr"+"ipt>");\r\n//]]>--></script><noscript><a href=''http://ads.centralpark.com/www/delivery/ck.php?n=a026fe8a&cb=INSERT_RANDOM_NUMBER_HERE'' target=''_blank''><img src=''http://ads.centralpark.com/www/delivery/avw.php?zoneid=15&n=a026fe8a'' border=''0'' alt='''' /></a></noscript>', '', '', '', 'lake800.jpg', '<a href="http://www.centralpark.com/pages/about-centralpark-com/staff/aric-boyles.html">Aric Boyles</a>', '', '', 0, '', '', 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 'Hallett Nature Sanctuary', 'Hallett Nature Sanctuary', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(189, '2005-10-09', 145, 2, 14, 'Erin Grenier', '', 'about-centralpark-com/staff/erin-grenier', 'CentralPark.com ::: The Complete Guide to New York City''s Central Park', 'Erin is a graduate of SCSU with a degree in Communication in Management, and Theatre. For the last three years <IMG height="165" alt="Erin Grenier" hspace="5" src="http://www.centralpark.com/pages/about/erin.jpg" width="150" align="right" vspace="5" border="0">she has worked as a Stage Manager for the critically lauded Keen Company (drama desk 2005) and has assisted for many years at the Tony award winning Long Wharf Theatre. She was also Company Manager at The Westport Country Playhouse and has worked with high caliber artists like Gene Wilder, Joanne Woodward, Al Pacino, Lynn Redgrave as well as playwrights David Auburn and Tim Blake Nelson. Erin spent the past year as a manager at Danny Meyer&rsquo;s renowned barbecue joint, Blue Smoke/Jazz Standard. A relentless underachiever Erin will be competing in next year&rsquo;s Tour de France, but only if her first year at Harvard Medical ends on time. \r\n<BR>\r\n<BR>Erin loves Central Park and is excited to be a part of the CentralPark.com team. \r\n<BR>\r\n<BR>.', 'CentralPark.com - Your first stop for information on Central Park and The Central Park Zoo!  Including extensive event listings, maps, attractions, sports, activities, history, essential info for tourists.', 'Central Park, NYC, New York City, ballfields, Balto, baseball, basketball, Belvedere Castle, Bethesda Fountain, Bethesda Terrace, bike, Boathouse, Bow Bridge, Calvert Vaux, Carousel, Central Park Conservancy, Central Park History, children, climbing wall, conservancy, family programs, Frederick Law Olmsted, Frederick Olmsted, Gates, Great Lawn, Greensward, Harlem Meer, Heckscher ballfields, Ice Skating, Imagine, Lasker Rink, Loeb Boathouse, merry-go-round, Metropolitan Museum, Obelisk, Olmsted, park, playground, public monuments, public park, Ramble, recreation programs, reservoir, r