(263, '2013-08-19', 12, 1, 15, 'Awards and Honors', '', 'about-centralpark-com/awards-and-honors', 'CentralPark.com Awards and Honors', '<p>On occasion our efforts here at CentralPark.com have been recognized by our peers in the internet fraternity.&nbsp; We are listing these awards here not only as a testament to our pursuit of excellence, but also in gratitude to those who took the time to bestow them. Thank you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And while some may seem a little more prestigious than others we did exercise some restraint in our list of testimonials.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="Time.com Top 50 Coolest Sites" src="http://img.timeinc.net/time/home/images/logo_timecnn.gif" style="height:82px; width:155px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Time Magazine&#39;s Website (in partnership with CNN) thinks we&#39;re cool! CentralPark.com was chosen as one of Time.com&#39;s <a href="http://www.time.com/time/business/article/0,8599,1222598,00.html#centralpark" target="_blank">Top 50 Coolest Websites</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="Yahoo! Publisher Network" src="/updata/ypn_logo.gif" style="height:33px; width:237px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Yahoo! Publisher Network recently chose CentralPark.com for their <a href="http://ypnblog.com/blog/2006/04/11/publisher-spotlight/" target="_blank">Publisher Spotlight</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.coolsiteoftheday.com/" target="_blank"><img alt="Cool Site of the Day" src="http://www.centralpark.com/updata/award_big.gif" style="height:110px; width:194px" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>We&#39;re so cool they made an award just for us! CentralPark.com was selected as the <a href="http://www.coolsiteoftheday.com/" target="_blank">CoolSiteoftheDay</a> on January 25th, 2006.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.macromedia.com/cfusion/showcase/index.cfm?event=sotdarchive&amp;year=2006&amp;month=1&amp;loc=en_us" target="_blank"><img alt="Macromedia Site of the Day" src="http://www.centralpark.com/updata/sod_badge_01-17-06.gif" style="height:92px; width:155px" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>CentralPark.com was featured as <a href="http://www.macromedia.com/cfusion/showcase/index.cfm?event=sotdarchive&amp;year=2006&amp;month=1&amp;loc=en_us" target="_blank">Macromedia Site of the Day</a> on January 17, 2006!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>{{ADSPACE_300_250}}</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.aawebmasters.com/" target="_blank"><img alt="American Association of Webmasters" src="/updata/AAWMGOLD.jpg" style="height:69px; width:123px" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>We won the 2006-2007 Gold Award from the <a href="http://www.aawebmasters.com/" target="_blank">American&nbsp;Association of Webmasters</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.invision-graphics.com/" target="_blank"><img alt="Invision Graphics Award" src="http://www.centralpark.com/updata/invision-graphics-award.jpg" style="float:left; height:45px; width:135px" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Our Invision Graphics Award for design.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.webthrower.com/" target="_blank"><img alt="WebThrower Design Award" src="http://www.centralpark.com/updata/award05gold.gif" style="height:86px; width:157px" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here&#39;s another award for design, this one from <a href="http://www.webthrower.com/" target="_blank">WebThrower.com</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.gadzillionthings.net/" target="_blank"><img alt="Gadzillion Award" src="http://www.centralpark.com/updata/1gazaward2.gif" style="height:140px; width:200px" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Who knew there were so many things to think about? Take a look at <a href="http://www.gadzillionthings.net/">www.gadzillionthings.net</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="Gold Award" src="http://www.centralpark.com/updata/AWDgold.gif" style="height:180px; width:190px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Our first award, the prestigious Advanced Web Design Award from <a href="http://www.web-design-miami.com/" target="_blank">Mackey Web Design</a>!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Next we have our Award for Excellence.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.animationplayhouse.com/" target="_blank"><img alt="Animation Playhouse Award" src="http://www.centralpark.com/updata/AnimationPlayhouseGoldAward.jpg" style="height:185px; width:159px" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>And here&#39;s our Animation Playhouse Gold Award.</p>\r\n', 'On occasion our efforts here at CentralPark.com have been recognized by our peers in the internet fraternity.', 'awards, honors, testimonials', 12.40, 3, '', '', '', '', 'bow_bridge.jpg', '<a href="http://www.centralpark.com/pages/about-centralpark-com/staff/rick-anderson.html">Rick Anderson</a>', '', '', 0, '', '', 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 'Awards and Honors', 'Awards and Honors', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2015-09-15 14:23:36'),
(264, '2012-06-08', 10, 1, 15, 'Central Park Medical Unit', '', 'general-info/central-park-medical-unit', 'Central Park Medical Unit', '<table style="background: #ffffff;" border="0" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" align="right">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center">\r\n<table style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% #ffffff; width: 200px;" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="right">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center"><img style="border: 0px initial initial;" title="Central Park Medical Unit" src="http://www.centralpark.com/updata/Image/CPMU.png" alt="Central Park Medical Unit" width="200" height="200" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style="font-size: xx-small;" align="right"><strong><a href="http://www.cpmu.com/" target="_blank">Central Park Medical Unit</a></strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>The Central Park Medical Unit, established in 1975, is made up of 150 volunteers and three ambulances that serve the Central Park area, providing medical service when needed.  The Unit is funded solely by private donations, and the medical services provided by the Unit are free of charge.  Each day, the Central Park Medical Unit receives dozens of calls, the majority of which are trauma calls.</p>\r\n<p>The Unit is often asked by the NYPD to assist in crises; they have aided New York City during both the World Trade Center bombing and the 2003 North America blackout.  Members of the Central Park Medical Unit are on standby at large events in Central Park, such as the NYC Marathon, concerts in Central Park, and the Macy''s Day Thanksgiving Parade.</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0 0 20px; text-align: right;"><small>&mdash; Jesse M. Wheeler </small></p>\r\n{{ADSPACE_300_250}}', 'The Central Park Medical Unit, established in 1975, is made up of 150 volunteers and three ambulances that serve the Central Park area, providing medical service when needed. ', 'Central Park Ambulance, Central Park Medical', 0.00, 0, '', '', '', '', 'mall.jpg', '<a href="http://www.centralpark.com/pages/about-centralpark-com/staff/rick-anderson.html">Rick Anderson</a>', '', '', 0, '', '', 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 'Central Park Medical Unit', 'Central Park Medical Unit', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(265, '2010-07-28', 16, 1, 14, 'Central Park Trivia', '', 'fun-stuff/central-park-trivia', 'Trivia', '<p>JTake a moment to answer the Central Park Trivia Question. We''ll be adding a new question each week and we''ll post the name of the CentralPark.com member to answer correctly first.</p>\r\n<p><strong>This Week''s Question:&nbsp;</strong> Who designed the fountain found in Central Park&rsquo;s Cherry Hill?</p>\r\n<form style="padding: 5px 2px;" action="/xmlrpc/trivia.php" method="post"> \r\n<table style="border: 1px solid #cccccc; background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% #ffffff; width: 380px;" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="4">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><label for="answer">Your Answer</label><span class="required">*</span></td>\r\n<td><input id="answer" maxlength="250" name="answer" size="30" value="Your Answer" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><label for="email">Name:</label><span class="required">*</span></td>\r\n<td><input id="name" maxlength="100" name="name" size="30" value="Your Name" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><label for="email">Email Address:</label><span class="required">*</span></td>\r\n<td><input id="email" maxlength="100" name="email" size="30" value="Your Email Address" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><span class="required">*</span> Required fields</td>\r\n<td align="right"><input name="submit" type="submit" value="Submit Answer" /> <input name="reset" type="reset" value="Reset" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</form> \r\n<hr />\r\n<p>July 21, 2010 Question: The Bow Bridge was constructed with ironwork provided by the same   company that constructed the dome of The Capitol in Washington, D.C.   What was the name of this company?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>Janes, Kirtland &amp; Co.</strong> first submitted by: We stumped you! No one submitted a correct answer.</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>July 14, 2010 Question: Today the Dairy is a visitors center. What was its original purpose?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>distributing milk to children</strong> first submitted by Makie</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>July 7, 2010 Question: Where in Central Park can visitors rent and use model sailboats?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>Conservatory Water</strong> first submitted by Bill Tracy</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>June 30, 2010 Question: The Conservatory Garden features three distinct style of gardens. What   are they?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>French, Italian and English style</strong> first submitted by Bill Tracy</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>June 23, 2010 Question: When was Strawberry Fields dedicated to John Lennon?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>1981</strong> first submitted by Barry</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>June 9th, 2010 Question:&nbsp; 					How much does the Obelisk in Central Park weigh?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>244 Tons</strong> first submitted by Dorothy Bosch  Keller</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>June 2nd, 2010 Question:&nbsp; The Good Morning America Concert Series is a new addition to  Central  Park concerts. How many years has GMA been at Rumsey Playfield?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>2 years</strong> first submitted by Daniel Krotine  Cleveland, Ohio</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>May 26th, 2010 Question: In what year was Central Park''s Grand Army Plaza completed?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>1916 </strong>first submitted by We stumped you guys  last week; no one submitted a correct answer!</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>May 19th, 2010 Question: The Reservoir covers 106-acres. How deep is it?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was:<strong> 40 feet deep</strong> first submitted by Emily James</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>May 12th, 2010 Question: How many acres is the Central Park Zoo?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>5 acres</strong> first submitted by John DeLaire</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>May 5th, 2010 Question: During what year did the free SummerStage events in Central Park begin?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>1985 </strong>first submitted by Bill Tracy</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>April 28st, 2010 Question:&nbsp; There are currently more than 20 playgrounds scattered throughout Central Park. During what decade was the first fully-equipped one constructed?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>The 1920s</strong> first submitted by Julie Hodorowski</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>April 21st, 2010 Question: When the city decided to create Central  Park in 1853, a number of  residents were displaced from their homes on  the site. About how many?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>Around 1,600</strong> first submitted by Perez</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>April 14th, 2010 Question: The Children''s Zoo in Central Park welcomed a new baby earlier in 2010.&nbsp; What was it?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>Mini Nubian Goat</strong> first submitted by Daniel Krotine, Cleveland Ohio</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>April 7th, 2010 Question: There is a fully functional National  Weather Station located inside of  Central Park.&nbsp; Where is it?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>Belvedere Castle</strong> first submitted by  Bill Tracy</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>March 31st, 2010 Question: In what movie does Central Park serve as the scene of a picnic shared by Sigourney Weaver and William Hurt?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>Eyewitness </strong>first  submitted by Daniel Krotine</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>March 24th, 2010 Question: How many horses does the Central Park  Carousel have?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>58 </strong>first  submitted by Cristina</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>March 17th, 2010 Question: Who was Balto?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>Balto was an Alaskan Malamute, who braved  fierce Arctic weather to deliver a badly needed antitoxin to save a  community from a diptheria epidemic </strong>first  submitted by Laurie</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>March 10th, 2010 Question: Name the 7 ornamental fountains that can  be located throughout Central  Park.</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>Angel of the Waters at Bethesda Terrace,  Burnett Fountain at Conservatory Garden''s English garden to the south,  Conservatory Garden''s Italian garden in the center, Untermyer Fountain  at Conservatory Garden''s French garden to the north, Cherry Hill, Sophie  Loeb Fountain, Pulitzer Fountain at Grand Army Plaza</strong> first  submitted by Alma</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>March 3rd, 2010 Question: Approximately how many people visit Central  Park each year?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>Aprox. 25 Million</strong> first submitted by  Jennifer Nicholas</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>February 24th, 2010 Question: What flower starts blooming in February  and is almost always the first plant to flower in the Central Park  Conservatory Garden?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>Snowdrops</strong> first submitted by Ramona  Desmond</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>February 18th, 2010 Question: What are the two locations that Bow Bridge, the most romantic place in Central Park, connects?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>Cherry Hill and The Ramble</strong> first submitted by Bill  Tracy</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>February 9nd, 2010 Question: What well-known 1970 romantic film''s  finale took place in Central Park?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>Love Story</strong> first submitted by Bill  Tracy</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>February 2nd, 2010 Question: Where was Manhattan''s first significant  community of African-American property owners?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>Seneca Village</strong> first submitted by  RocioA</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>January 28th, 2010 Question: What are the two goat breeds combined to produce a Mini-Nubian goat, such as the one recently born at the Central Park Zoo?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>Cross between Nigerian Dwarf goats and Nubian Goats</strong> first submitted by Bill Tracy</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>January 20th, 2010 Question: How long is the run that loops around the park on Park Drive?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>Approximately 6 miles</strong> first submitted by Grannie Annie Singer</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>January 13th, 2010 Question: The Wollman Rink was featured in what late-90s film with Brad Pitt?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>The Devil''s Own</strong> first submitted by J. Koerpel</p>\r\n<p><center style="page-break-after: always;"></center></p>\r\n<p>July 5th, 2009 Question: Where in Central Park is the <strong>Moth Tree</strong>?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>Between 72nd St. and the Boathouse</strong> first submitted by W. Tracy</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>June 6th, 2009 Question: Who built the <strong>Vanderbilt Gates</strong> of Conservatory Garden?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>George B. Post </strong>designed them and had them built in Paris first submitted by Jeffrey L. Smith</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>May 19th, 2009 Question: Where is <strong>Azalea Walk</strong>?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>South of Eaglevale Arch</strong> first submitted by YorkiesInHeaven</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>April 29th, 2009 Question: Where was <strong>Marble Arch</strong>?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: It was at the south end of the Mall at 66th St. - first submitted by delaire15</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>April 7th, 2009 Question: Where was <strong>Outset Arch</strong>?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: It was over the bridle path at the SW corner of the <strong>Zoo</strong> - first submitted by MGraff</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>March 30th, 2009 Question: Where was <strong>Spur Rock Arch</strong>?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: It was near<strong> Heckscher Playground</strong> at 61st St and 7th Ave. - first submitted by WTracy</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>March 4th, 2009 Question: Where did <strong>Winterdale Arch</strong> get its name?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: It was named for thar section of the West Drive known as <strong>Winter Drive</strong> - first submitted by celia805</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>February 9th, 2009 Question:How large, in acreage, is the Reservoir?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>106 Acres - </strong>first submitted by Orlando Pearsons</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>January 27th, 2009 Question: The original American Museum of Natural History was designed by Vaux and Mould and opened in 1877 on what city named square?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>Manhattan Square - </strong>first submitted by S Rizzo</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>January 16th, 2009 Question: Two men are primarily credited with the inception of Central Park - William Cullen Bryant was one - who was the other?</p>\r\n<p>The Correct Answer was: <strong>Andrew Jackson Downing - </strong>first submitted by DM Rainforth</p>\r\n<hr />', 'Take a moment to answer the Central Park Trivia Question. We''ll be adding a new question each week and we''ll post the name of the CentralPark.com member to answer correctly first.', 'central park trivia', 18.80, 4, '', '', '', '', 'bow_bridge_gondola.jpg', '<a href="http://www.centralpark.com/pages/about-centralpark-com/staff/rick-anderson.html">Rick Anderson</a>', '', '', 0, '', '', 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 'Central Park Trivia', 'Central Park Trivia', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(266, '2015-07-08', 2, 1, 15, 'Bridges of Central Park', '', 'attractions/bridges-of-central-park', 'Bridges of Central Park', '<table style="background: #ffffff;" border="0" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" align="right">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center">\r\n<table style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% #ffffff; width: 200px;" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="right">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center"><a title="bridge in central park" rel="lightbox-guide" href="http://www.centralpark.com/updata/Image/attractions/bridge-in-central-park-f.jpg"> <img src="http://www.centralpark.com/updata/Image/attractions/bridges-of-central-park.jpg" border="0" alt="Bridges of Central Park" width="200" /> </a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style="font-size: xx-small;" align="right"><strong>bridge in central park</strong> by <em><a href="http://www.centralpark.com/members/profile21669.html" target="_blank">cameragirl </a></em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h3>Bank Rock Bridge (btw 77th and 78th streets)</h3>\r\n<p>Entirely recreated in 2009 as a sturdier replica of the original, Bank Rock Bridge had suffered the ill effects of the elements for years after its construction in 1860.  It was replaced with a simple wood and pipe railing bridge in1935, but its more recent restoration returned to the bridge the grandeur it once had.</p>\r\n<p><span style="color: #008000;"><br /></span></p>\r\n<h3>Balcony Bridge (77th street)</h3>\r\n<p>Made primarily of schist and sandstone, the Balcony Bridge was named for its two small balconies that offer resting points for those wishing to stop and take in the view.  It was built in 1860 and is decorated with quatrefoil cutouts.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3><a href="http://www.centralpark.com/guide/attractions/bridges-of-central-park/bow-bridge.html">Bow Bridge</a> (74th street)</h3>\r\n<p>The stately Bow Bridge was fashioned by Calvert Vaux and Jacob Wrey Mould in a Classic Greek style with Renaissance Gothic foliate designs.  At a length of 60 feet, it provides a pathway from the Ramble to Cherry Hill.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div>{{ADSPACE_300_250}}</div>\r\n<h3>Dalehead Arch (64th street)</h3>\r\n<p>This sandstone and brownstone arch also includes the quatrefoil cutout design that appears on many of the original 19th century bridges in Central Park.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Eaglevale Bridge (77th street)</h3>\r\n<p>Designed by the architect Josiah Cleveland Cady, this gneiss bridge was constructed in 1890.  At one time, it provided a path to the Ladies'' Pond, which has been replaced with a playground.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3><a href="http://www.centralpark.com/guide/attractions/bridges-of-central-park/gapstow-bridge.html">Gapstow Bridge</a> (62nd street)</h3>\r\n<p>From the Gapstow Bridge, one can see skaters at Wollman''s Rink in winter, the Victorian Gardens in summer, and the Plaza Hotel and city skyscrapers in any season.  This 76 foot long bridge was constructed by Howard and Caudwell in 1896 and is made of Manhattan schist.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Glade Arch (78th street)</h3>\r\n<p>Glade Arch, one of earliest bridges designed by Calvert Vaux, is made of New Brunswick sandstone. In 1980 a large portion of the fence posts were damaged by a snow plow leading to a complete restoration the following year.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Glen Span Bridge (102nd street)</h3>\r\n<p>This gneiss arch that provides an entrance to the Ravine was first constructed of simple wood 1865.  It was later replaced with the more enduring stone and sits east of the Pool and west of the Loch.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Gothic Bridge (94th street)</h3>\r\n<p>The beautiful Central Park Gothic Bridge was made of steel and cast iron in 1864, when it was designed by Vaux.  This bridge gets its name from the Gothic Cathedral style curves of the ironwork on the spandrels.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Pine Bank Bridge (62nd street)</h3>\r\n<p>Another cast iron bridge, Pink Bank Bridge extends towards Heckscher Playground and was first built in1861 by J.B. and W.W. Cornell Ironworks.  It was then renovated in 1984, as it had fallen into disrepair over the years.  Its intricate designs make it a must-see for those interested in architecture.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Reservoir Bridge (85th street)</h3>\r\n<p>One of the two bridges that are situated near the Reservoir, this bridge consists of a wooden footpath and is decorated with elegant floral scrolls and spiraling leaves along all 38 feet.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Reservoir Bridge (94th street)</h3>\r\n<p>This 15-foot cast iron bridge is located near the North Gatehouse, and bears a striking resemblance to the Gothic Bridge because of its design.  This bridge was designed by Calvert Vaux and constructed in 1864.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Terrace Bridge (72nd street)</h3>\r\n<p>Bethesda Terrace, inspired by the designs of the Palace of Versailles, was envisioned as one of the focal points of the entire Park by its creators.  Fashioned out of New Brunswick sandstone, the Terrace stands at 16 feet high and 29 feet wide.  A highly popular Central Park attraction, the Terrace is also known for containing the Bethesda Fountain.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0 0 20px; text-align: right;"><small>&mdash; Jesse M. Wheeler </small></p>', 'There are many bridges in Central Park that not only function as pathways but also contribute greatly to the architectural beauty of the park. They range from wooden to steel to cast iron to stone and rock. ', 'Bank Rock Bridge, Balcony Bridge, Bow Bridge, Dalehead Arch, Eaglevale Bridge, Gapstow Bridge, Glen Span Bridge, Gothic Bridge, Pine Bank Bridge, Reservoir Bridge, Terrace Bridge', 0.00, 0, '<script type=''text/javascript''><!--//<![CDATA[\r\n   var m3_u = (location.protocol==''https:''?''https://ads.centralpark.com/www/delivery/ajs.php'':''http://ads.centralpark.com/www/delivery/ajs.php'');\r\n   var