(348, '2012-04-03', 332, 1, 15, 'Magnolia Soulangiana', '', 'conservatory-garden-flowers/magnolia-soulangiana', 'Magnolia Soulangiana ''Galaxy'' - Central Park Flowers', '<div id="flowers">\r\n<h1>Magnolia Soulangiana</h1>\r\n<table style="margin: 0 0 10px 10px;" border="0" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center">\r\n<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center"><img src="/usr/media/flowers/magnolia.jpg" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="175" align="middle" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>The magnolia soulangiana tree is a member of the Magnoliaceae family. It is very popular throughout the United States and in England. It is a hybrid tree, and is unusually hardy and resistant to chill. Because of this, it is a popular tree in Central Park. Its leaves range in color from dark green to bronze, while its flowers can be found in pink, white, or purple. Its large blooms are characterized by lush, wide petals, which appear in April and throughout the spring, and its flowers have a mild, pleasant scent.</p>\r\n<ul class="buttons">\r\n<li class="f-prev"><a title="Previous flower" href="/guide/conservatory-garden-flowers/japanese-lilac.html">Previous flower</a></li>\r\n<li class="f-next"><a title="Next flower" href="/guide/conservatory-garden-flowers/oakleaf-hydrangea.html">Next flower</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>', 'The Saucer Magnolia is a variety of tree whose early spring flowers are especially large and have a deep rose flush to their outer petals. The specimen in the Conservatory Garden replaced a Magnolia which had succumbed to old age about five years ago. Magnolias are fast growers; in another five years, it should once again provide ample shade to the same idyllic corner of the Garden.', 'Magnolia Soulangiana, Conservatory Garden, Central Park Garden, Bloom Schedule, garden, flowers, central park flowers ', 0.00, 0, '', '', '', 'gardens', 'conservatory-garden.jpg', '<A HREF="http://andrewprokos.com/photos/new-york/central-park/">Andrew Prokos</a>', '', '', 16, '/usr/media/flowers/flowers.css', '', 1, 1, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 'Magnolia Soulangiana', 'Magnolia Soulangiana', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(349, '2012-04-03', 332, 1, 15, 'Oakleaf Hydrangea', '', 'conservatory-garden-flowers/oakleaf-hydrangea', 'Oakleaf Hydrangea (Hydrangea quercifolia) - Central Park Flowers', '<div id="flowers">\r\n<h1>Oakleaf Hydrangea</h1>\r\n<table style="margin: 0 0 10px 10px;" border="0" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center">\r\n<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center"><img src="/usr/media/flowers/oakleaf-hydrangea.jpg" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="175" align="middle" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>The oakleaf hydrangea is a deciduous tree that thrives in sun or partial shade. It generally requires well-drained soil, and can grow to a height of up to 8 feet. Its thick, green, leathery leaves are large and help to keep the tree cool in warm weather. The oakleaf hydrangea is part of the Hydrangeaceae family, and thrives throughout much of the United States. Its delicate, small, white flowers have made it a popular tree in public parks as well as private gardens. This tree, which has a shrub-like appearance, is one of the largest members of the Hydrangeaceae family. It blooms throughout the spring, summer, and even into autumn.</p>\r\n<ul class="buttons">\r\n<li class="f-prev"><a title="Previous flower" href="/guide/conservatory-garden-flowers/magnolia-soulangiana.html">Previous flower</a></li>\r\n<li class="f-next"><a title="Next flower" href="/guide/conservatory-garden-flowers/peony.html">Next flower</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>', 'In the Conservatory Garden, the Oakleaf Hydrangea anchors the middle of the annual bed number five in the South Garden. This native shrub of the southeastern United States is truly an all-season plant.', 'Oakleaf Hydrangea, Hydrangea quercifolia, Conservatory Garden, Central Park Garden, Bloom Schedule, garden, flowers, central park flowers ', 0.00, 0, '', '', '', 'gardens', 'conservatory-garden.jpg', '<A HREF="http://andrewprokos.com/photos/new-york/central-park/">Andrew Prokos</a>', '', '', 17, '/usr/media/flowers/flowers.css', '', 1, 1, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 'Oakleaf Hydrangea', 'Oakleaf Hydrangea', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(350, '2012-04-03', 332, 1, 15, 'Peony', '', 'conservatory-garden-flowers/peony', 'Peony (Paeonia) - Central Park Flowers', '<div id="flowers">\r\n<h1>Peony</h1>\r\n<table style="margin: 0 0 10px 10px;" border="0" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center">\r\n<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center"><img src="/usr/media/flowers/peony.jpg" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="175" align="middle" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>This appealing plant is a member of the Paeoniaceae family. These perennial flowers are distinctive because of their lush, multilayered shape. They can be found in a huge variety of colors, including cream, pink, red, coral, white, yellow, black, and ivory. Peonies can tolerate cold weather well, making them a natural addition to the Conservatory Garden. Since cold weather is a requirement to produce the peonies'' delicate blooms, they are usually most prolific after a harsh winter. In Central Park, peonies bloom most markedly in June, and continue throughout the summer and into the fall. The delicate scent of the peony makes this flower a favorite in the Park.</p>\r\n<ul class="buttons">\r\n<li class="f-prev"><a title="Previous flower" href="/guide/conservatory-garden-flowers/oakleaf-hydrangea.html">Previous flower</a></li>\r\n<li class="f-next"><a title="Next flower" href="/guide/conservatory-garden-flowers/phlox.html">Next flower</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>', 'This hardy plant makes its appearance in the Conservatory Garden in early June and lasts all the way through September. They are herbaceous perennial plants that grow from one to two feet tall.', 'Peony, Paeonia, Conservatory Garden, Central Park Garden, Bloom Schedule, garden, flowers, central park flowers ', 0.00, 0, '', '', '', 'gardens', 'conservatory-garden.jpg', '<A HREF="http://andrewprokos.com/photos/new-york/central-park/">Andrew Prokos</a>', '', '', 18, '/usr/media/flowers/flowers.css', '', 1, 1, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 'Peony', 'Peony', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(351, '2012-04-03', 332, 1, 15, 'Phlox', '', 'conservatory-garden-flowers/phlox', 'Phlox - Central Park Flowers', '<div id="flowers">\r\n<h1>Phlox</h1>\r\n<table style="margin: 0 0 10px 10px;" border="0" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center">\r\n<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center"><img src="/usr/media/flowers/phlox.jpg" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="175" align="middle" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>The phlox is a tall and stately plant with an unusually short blooming season. However, its striking appearance and vibrant color are very memorable. Phlox is a member of the Polemoniaceae family and is prolific throughout North America, even in very cold regions. Phlox flowers bloom in the summer and in the fall, and may be blue, red, cream, or violet. Their fragrant blooms help them create the ethereal atmosphere of the Conservatory Garden. Phlox is particularly popular in the garden as a border for its large flower beds. This plant''s height, which can be as great as 3 feet, makes it stand out.</p>\r\n<ul class="buttons">\r\n<li class="f-prev"><a title="Previous flower" href="/guide/conservatory-garden-flowers/peony.html">Previous flower</a></li>\r\n<li class="f-next"><a title="Next flower" href="/guide/conservatory-garden-flowers/purple-coneflower.html">Next flower</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>', 'The lovely flowers range in color: from pale blue to bright red to white, and bloom in Central Park from July to September. The plants provide some of the most vibrantly colorful blooms that can be found in Conservatory Garden in early fall.', 'Phlox, Conservatory Garden, Central Park Garden, Bloom Schedule, garden, flowers, central park flowers ', 0.00, 0, '', '', '', 'gardens', 'conservatory-garden.jpg', '<A HREF="http://andrewprokos.com/photos/new-york/central-park/">Andrew Prokos</a>', '', '', 19, '/usr/media/flowers/flowers.css', '', 1, 1, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 'Phlox', 'Phlox', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(352, '2012-04-03', 332, 1, 15, 'Purple Coneflower', '', 'conservatory-garden-flowers/purple-coneflower', 'Purple Coneflower (Echinacea purpurea) - Central Park Flowers', '<div id="flowers">\r\n<h1>Purple Coneflower</h1>\r\n<table style="margin: 0 0 10px 10px;" border="0" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center">\r\n<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center"><img src="/usr/media/flowers/coneflower.jpg" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="175" align="middle" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>The purple coneflower, commonly known as echinacea, is a hallmark of the Conservatory Garden. This plant is well known for its medicinal properties, but many people do not realize how extraordinarily beautiful it is. Its rich, dark plum tones make it unique among some of the pastel colors in the Garden. This plant is a member of the Asteraceae family.</p>\r\n<ul class="buttons">\r\n<li class="f-prev"><a title="Previous flower" href="/guide/conservatory-garden-flowers/phlox.html">Previous flower</a></li>\r\n<li class="f-next"><a title="Next flower" href="/guide/conservatory-garden-flowers/rose-of-sharon.html">Next flower</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>', 'The common Purple Coneflower (Echinacea purpurea) is a lovely, sturdy, perennial plant, one of the signature flowers of the mid-summer Conservatory Garden.', 'Purple Coneflower, Echinacea purpurea, Conservatory Garden, Central Park Garden, Bloom Schedule, garden, flowers, central park flowers ', 0.00, 0, '', '', '', 'gardens', 'conservatory-garden.jpg', '<A HREF="http://andrewprokos.com/photos/new-york/central-park/">Andrew Prokos</a>', '', '', 20, '/usr/media/flowers/flowers.css', '', 1, 1, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 'Purple Coneflower', 'Purple Coneflower', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(353, '2012-04-03', 332, 1, 15, 'Rose Of Sharon', '', 'conservatory-garden-flowers/rose-of-sharon', 'Rose Of Sharon (Hibiscus Syriacus) - Central Park Flowers', '<div id="flowers">\r\n<h1>Rose Of Sharon</h1>\r\n<table style="margin: 0 0 10px 10px;" border="0" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center">\r\n<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center"><img src="/usr/media/flowers/rose-of-sharon.jpg" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="175" align="middle" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>The rose of Sharon is part of the Malvaceae family. It is also known as the crocus or shrub Althea. The rose of Sharon traces its heritage to biblical times, and its name is derived from the Hebrew word for crocus. It is also the national flower of South Korea. It is easy to see why this flower is part of one of the most multicultural gardens in the world. The rose of Sharon is usually a light, delicate pink; it is characterized by wide, thin petals. It is prolific throughout the United States and blooms from June until September.</p>\r\n<ul class="buttons">\r\n<li class="f-prev"><a title="Previous flower" href="/guide/conservatory-garden-flowers/purple-coneflower.html">Previous flower</a></li>\r\n<li class="f-next"><a title="Next flower" href="/guide/conservatory-garden-flowers/rose.html">Next flower</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>', 'Easily one of the most colorful names of all the inhabitants of Hollyhocksthe Conservatory Garden, is Rose of Sharon. It originated in 1611, when it was used in the King James Version of the Bible.', 'Rose Of Sharon, Hibiscus Syriacus, Conservatory Garden, Central Park Garden, Bloom Schedule, garden, flowers, central park flowers ', 0.00, 0, '', '', '', 'gardens', 'conservatory-garden.jpg', '<A HREF="http://andrewprokos.com/photos/new-york/central-park/">Andrew Prokos</a>', '', '', 21, '/usr/media/flowers/flowers.css', '', 1, 1, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 'Rose Of Sharon', 'Rose Of Sharon', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(354, '2012-04-03', 332, 1, 15, 'Rose', '', 'conservatory-garden-flowers/rose', 'Rose (Rosa) - Central Park Flowers', '<div id="flowers">\r\n<h1>Rose</h1>\r\n<table style="margin: 0 0 10px 10px;" border="0" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center">\r\n<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center"><img src="/usr/media/flowers/rose.jpg" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="175" align="middle" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>The Conservatory Garden would not be complete without a selection of roses, one of the most popular flowers and America. The rose is a member of the Rosaceae family. Roses grow throughout the world, especially North America, Africa, and Europe. The rose blooms throughout the summer and into the mid fall. Many varieties of roses can be found in the Conservatory Garden, especially white, red, pink, and other vibrant colors. Roses grow on shrubs that can reach several feet tall, and are known for the prickly thorns that appear on their stems.</p>\r\n<ul class="buttons">\r\n<li class="f-prev"><a title="Previous flower" href="/guide/conservatory-garden-flowers/rose-of-sharon.html">Previous flower</a></li>\r\n<li class="f-next"><a title="Next flower" href="/guide/conservatory-garden-flowers/snowdrops.html">Next flower</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>', 'Roses are the royalty of the flowering plant kingdom, their long history including many instances of famous namesakes, critically acclaimed collections and one rather notable war. As would be expected, they form a critical element to the Conservatory Garden and can be found throughout.', 'roses, Conservatory Garden, Central Park Garden, Bloom Schedule, garden, flowers, central park flowers ', 0.00, 0, '', '', '', 'gardens', 'conservatory-garden.jpg', '<A HREF="http://andrewprokos.com/photos/new-york/central-park/">Andrew Prokos</a>', '', '', 22, '/usr/media/flowers/flowers.css', '', 1, 1, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 'Rose', 'Rose', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(355, '2012-04-03', 332, 1, 15, 'Snowdrops', '', 'conservatory-garden-flowers/snowdrops', 'Snowdrops (Galanthus nivalis) - Central Park Flowers', '<div id="flowers">\r\n<h1>Snowdrops</h1>\r\n<table style="margin: 0 0 10px 10px;" border="0" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center">\r\n<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center"><img src="/usr/media/flowers/snowdrops.jpg" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="175" align="middle" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>Snowdrops stand out because they are small and slender. These members of the Amaryllidaceae family are perennials that grow from bulbs and can be found throughout the United States and Europe. The bulbs of this lovely plant are poisonous, and must not be eaten. Snowdrops are characterized by small white blossoms that droop from the end of their slender green stalks. They are among the first flowers to bloom when spring comes and last through the summer. The small, white flowers of snowdrops provide a delicate counterpoint to the bolder and brighter colors that appear throughout the Conservatory Garden.</p>\r\n<ul class="buttons">\r\n<li class="f-prev"><a title="Previous flower" href="/guide/conservatory-garden-flowers/rose.html">Previous flower</a></li>\r\n<li class="f-next"><a title="Next flower" href="/guide/conservatory-garden-flowers/spiraea.html">Next flower</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>', 'Snowdrops are spread throughout the Conservatory Garden and can be found in almost all the flowering beds. The major benefit of planting Snowdrops is their early arrival.', 'Snowdrops, Galanthus nivalis, Conservatory Garden, Central Park Garden, Bloom Schedule, garden, flowers, central park flowers ', 0.00, 0, '', '', '', 'gardens', 'conservatory-garden.jpg', '<A HREF="http://andrewprokos.com/photos/new-york/central-park/">Andrew Prokos</a>', '', '', 23, '/usr/media/flowers/flowers.css', '', 1, 1, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 'Snowdrops', 'Snowdrops', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(356, '2012-04-03', 332, 1, 15, 'Spiraea', '', 'conservatory-garden-flowers/spiraea', 'Spiraea (Rosaceae spiraeoideae) - Central Park Flowers', '<div id="flowers">\r\n<h1>Spiraea</h1>\r\n<table style="margin: 0 0 10px 10px;" border="0" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center">\r\n<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center"><img src="/usr/media/flowers/spiraea-japonica.jpg" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="175" align="middle" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>Spiraea is a deciduous shrub that sprouts delicate white blooms throughout April and May. This plant grows best in full sun or mild shade and prefers well-drained soil. This is a hardy plant that thrives even in cold or harsh climates, making it an excellent choice for the Conservatory Garden. The spiraea bush grows as tall as 8 feet and sometimes displays red foliage in the fall. The shrubs are common throughout Asia as well as the United States.</p>\r\n<ul class="buttons">\r\n<li class="f-prev"><a title="Previous flower" href="/guide/conservatory-garden-flowers/snowdrops.html">Previous flower</a></li>\r\n<li class="f-next"><a title="Next flower" href="/guide/conservatory-garden-flowers/squill.html">Next flower</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>', 'Spiraea bloom in the Conservatory Garden from April to May and form a lovely component to the spring landscape. With their clusters of bright white or pink petals, they compliment the more colorful blooms that decorate the garden beds during the early months of summer.', 'Spiraea, Conservatory Garden, Central Park Garden, Bloom Schedule, garden, flowers, central park flowers ', 0.00, 0, '', '', '', 'gardens', 'conservatory-garden.jpg', '<A HREF="http://andrewprokos.com/photos/new-york/central-park/">Andrew Prokos</a>', '', '', 24, '/usr/media/flowers/flowers.css', '', 1, 1, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 'Spiraea', 'Spiraea', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(357, '2012-04-03', 332, 1, 15, 'Squill', '', 'conservatory-garden-flowers/squill', 'Squill (Scilla) - Central Park Flowers', '<div id="flowers">\r\n<h1>Squill</h1>\r\n<table style="margin: 0 0 10px 10px;" border="0" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center">\r\n<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center"><img src="/usr/media/flowers/squill.jpg" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="175" align="middle" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>The squill is a small flower that blooms perennially and is a member of the Asparagaceae family. It is prolific throughout Asia as well as Europe and the United States. It blooms throughout the spring and is notable for its slight stature and delicate bloom. This plant grows only 6 to 8 inches tall, but can still withstand cold temperatures. It is frequently used as a border plant in the Conservatory Garden, though it sometimes appears in other locations as well. Its long petals can be white, purple, pink, cream, or violet. It is sometimes called scilla.</p>\r\n<ul class="buttons">\r\n<li class="f-prev"><a title="Previous flower" href="/guide/conservatory-garden-flowers/spiraea.html">Previous flower</a></li>\r\n<li class="f-next"><a title="Next flower" href="/guide/conservatory-garden-flowers/tulip.html">Next flower</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>', 'In the Conservatory Garden, Squill are one of the many species of colorful flowers that bloom in spring; their appearance heralding the arrival of warmer weather, longer days and balmy afternoons spent among the flagrant blooms.', 'Squill, Scilla, Conservatory Garden, Central Park Garden, Bloom Schedule, garden, flowers, central park flowers ', 0.00, 0, '', '', '', 'gardens', 'conservatory-garden.jpg', '<A HREF="http://andrewprokos.com/photos/new-york/central-park/">Andrew Prokos</a>', '', '', 25, '/usr/media/flowers/flowers.css', '', 1, 1, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 'Squill', 'Squill', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(358, '2012-04-03', 332, 1, 15, 'Tulip', '', 'conservatory-garden-flowers/tulip', 'Tulip (Tulipa) - Central Park Flowers', '<div id="flowers">\r\n<h1>Tulip</h1>\r\n<table style="margin: 0 0 10px 10px;" border="0" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center">\r\n<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center"><img src="/usr/media/flowers/tulip.jpg" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="175" align="middle" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>The tulip is one of the most easily recognized and most popular flowers in the United States, and is an important part of the Conservatory Garden. In fact, the Conservatory Garden is home to more than 20,000 tulips each year. At the Garden''s annual Tulip Toss, volunteers remove the tulip bulbs from the ground and transplant them to other areas of the park. Tulips, which are members of the Liliaceae family, are very easy to maintain because they are bulbous perennials. These luscious blooms are prolific throughout Europe, parts of Africa, and parts of Asia. Tulips grow in a staggering variety of colors, among them, orange, white, pink, yellow, and red.</p>\r\n<ul class="buttons">\r\n<li class="f-prev"><a title="Previous flower" href="/guide/conservatory-garden-flowers/squill.html">Previous flower</a></li>\r\n<li class="f-next"><a title="Next" href="/guide/conservatory-garden-flowers/water-lilies.html">Next flower</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>', 'The Tulip is a member of the Lily (Liliaceae) family of flowering plants. They are perennial bulbous plants, growing four to twenty-seven inches in height, with a small number of strap-shaped, waxy-textured green leaves and large flowers with six petals. They are one of the most recognizable inhabitants of the Conservatory Garden and come in a wide variety of brilliant colors.', 'Tulip, Conservatory Garden, Central Park Garden, Bloom Schedule, garden, flowers, central park flowers ', 0.00, 0, '', '', '', 'gardens', 'conservatory-garden.jpg', '<A HREF="http://andrewprokos.com/photos/new-york/central-park/">Andrew Prokos</a>', '', '', 26, '/usr/media/flowers/flowers.css', '', 1, 1, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 'Tulip', 'Tulip', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(359, '2012-04-03', 332, 1, 15, 'Water Lilies', '', 'conservatory-garden-flowers/water-lilies', 'Water Lilies (Nympheas) - Central Park Flowers', '<div id="flowers">\r\n<h1>Water Lilies</h1>\r\n<table style="margin: 0 0 10px 10px;" border="0" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center">\r\n<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="right" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td align="center"><img src="/usr/media/flowers/waterlily.jpg" border="0" alt="" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="175" align="middle" /></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>Water lilies can be found in a picturesque pool amidst the flower beds of the Conservatory Garden. Their bold, pink blooms create a brilliant contrast to the deep green leaves and dark water. Water lilies are a member of the Nymphaeaceae family. The roots of these unusual plants are embedded in the soil deep beneath the surface of the water, while their leaves and flowers float freely. Water lilies bloom throughout the summer and are one of the most interesting and unusual plants in Central Park.</p>\r\n<ul class="buttons">\r\n<li class="f-prev"><a title="Previous flower" href="/guide/conservatory-garden-flowers/tulip.html">Previous flower</a></li>\r\n<li class="f-next">&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>', 'The Water Lilies in the English section of Conservatory Garden reside in a quiet pool at the center of the flower beds. Above the placid water stands a statue sculpted by Bessie Potter Vonnoh. It commemorates "The Secret Garden," the classic children''s book by Frances Hodgson Burnett.', 'Water Lilies, Nympheas, Conservatory Garden, Central Park Garden, Bloom Schedule, garden, flowers, central park flowers ', 0.00, 0, '', '', '', 'gardens', 'conservatory-garden.jpg', '<A HREF="http://andrewprokos.com/photos/new-york/central-park/">Andrew Prokos</a>', '', '', 27, '/usr/media/flowers/flowers.css', '', 1, 1, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 'Water Lilies', 'Water Lilies', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(360, '2013-08-20', 332, 1, 15, 'The Conservatory Garden Bloom Schedule', '', 'conservatory-garden-flowers/bloom-schedule', 'Conservatory Garden Bloom Schedule in Central Park', '<div id="flowers">\r\n<p>Discover when your favorite flower will be decorating the garden and also find out fascinating background facts about each bloom. Enjoy!</p>\r\n<dl class="schedule"> <dt><a title="Astilbe (June - August)" href="page.php?pid=334">Astilbe</a></dt> <dd>June - August </dd> <dt><a title="Baby''s breath (June - July)" href="page.php?pid=343">Baby''s breath </a></dt> <dd>June - July</dd> <dt><a title="Coneflower (July - September)" href="page.php?pid=335">Coneflower </a></dt> <dd>July - September</dd> <dt><a title="Cornelian Cherry (March)" href="page.php?pid=336">Cornelian Cherry </a></dt> <dd>March </dd> <dt><a title="Crabapples (April - May)" href="page.php?pid=337">Crabapples </a></dt> <dd>April - May </dd> <dt><a title="Daffodils (March - May)" href="page.php?pid=338">Daffodils </a></dt> <dd>March - May </dd> <dt><a title="Daylillies (June - August)" href="page.php?pid=339">Daylillies </a></dt> <dd>June - August</dd> <dt><a title="Grape Hyacinths (April - May)" href="page.php?pid=341">Grape Hyacinths</a></dt> <dd>April - May </dd> <dt><a title="Hellebores (March - April)" href="page.php?pid=344">Hellebores </a></dt> <dd>March - April </dd> <dt><a title="Hollyhocks (June - July)" href="page.php?pid=345">Hollyhocks </a></dt> <dd>June - July </dd> <dt><a title="Irises (March &amp; May)" href="page.php?pid=346">Irises </a></dt> <dd>March &amp; May </dd> </dl>{{ADSPACE_300_250}} <dl class="schedule"><dt><a title="Japanese Anemone (July - October)" href="page.php?pid=333">Japanese Anemone </a></dt> <dd>July - October</dd> <dt><a title="Lilacs, French (May)" href="page.php?pid=340">Lilacs, French </a></dt> <dd>May </dd> <dt><a title="Lilacs, Japanese (June)" href="page.php?pid=347">Lilacs, Japanese</a></dt> <dd>June </dd> <dt><a title="Magnolias (April - May)" href="page.php?pid=348">Magnolias </a></dt> <dd>April - May </dd> <dt><a title="Oakleaf Hydrangea (July - September)" href="page.php?pid=349">Oakleaf Hydrangea </a></dt> <dd>July - September</dd> <dt><a title="Ornamental Grasses (July - October)" href="page.php?pid=342">Ornamental Grasses</a></dt> <dd>July - October</dd> <dt><a title="Peony (June)" href="page.php?pid=350">Peony </a></dt> <dd>June </dd> <dt><a title="Phlox (June - September)" href="page.php?pid=351">Phlox </a></dt> <dd>June - September</dd> <dt><a title="Purple Coneflower (July - September)" href="page.php?pid=352">Purple Coneflower </a></dt> <dd>July - September</dd> <dt><a title="Rose of Sharon (July - September)" href="page.php?pid=353">Rose of Sharon</a></dt> <dd>July - September</dd> <dt><a title="Roses (June - October)" href="page.php?pid=354">Roses </a></dt> <dd>June - October</dd> <dt><a title="Snowdrops (February - March)" href="page.php?pid=355">Snowdrops </a></dt> <dd>February - March </dd> <dt><a title="Spiraea (April - May)" href="page.php?pid=356">Spiraea </a></dt> <dd>April - May </dd> <dt><a title="Squill (April - May)" href="page.php?pid=357">Squill </a></dt> <dd>April - May </dd> <dt><a title="Tulips (April - May)" href="page.php?pid=358">Tulips </a></dt> <dd>April - May </dd> <dt><a title="Water Lilies (June - October)" href="page.php?pid=359">Water Lilies </a></dt> <dd>June - October</dd> </dl>\r\n<div class="clear separator">&nbsp;</div>\r\n</div>', 'The Central Park Conservatory Garden Bloom Schedule - CentralPark.com', 'Central Park flowers, central park bloom schedule, central park conservatory garden flowers', 0.00, 0, '', '', '', 'gardens', 'conservatory-garden.jpg', '<A HREF="http://andrewprokos.com/photos/new-york/central-park/">Andrew Prokos</a>', '', '', 0, '/usr/media/flowers/flowers.css', '', 0, 1, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 'Bloom Schedule', 'Bloom Schedule', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00'),
(361, '2009-05-19', 332, 1, 14, 'Starbright Floral Design', '', 'conservatory-garden-flowers/starbright-floral-design', 'Starbright Floral Design - CentralPark.com', '<div id="gardensCon">\r\n<div class="logo"><img src="/usr/media/gardens/section.logo.png" alt="" width="396" height="148" /></div>\r\n<div class="separator">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<p>The Conservatory Garden section of Central Park is the only formal garden in all of Central Park and remains a hidden gem at 105th St. and Fifth Ave.</p>\r\n<p>Starflor Floral Designs has sponsored a Conservatory Gardens Microsite that features fascinating information about the Twenty-eight blooming plants, shrubs and trees that comprise this amazing urban oasis.</p>\r\n<p>They have also combined with CentralPark.com to produce the Starflor Conservatory Garden Virtual Bouquet - a unique way to send flowers to someone you care about.</p>\r\n<p>Use any, or all, of the gorgeous blooms that grace the Conservatory Garden throughout the year to create a virtual bouquet that you can email to a friend, or upload to our online gallery.</p>\r\n<p>So, take a minute to stroll through the garden (virtually) and then send a Central Park floral design to someone special.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class="separator">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><a title="Starflor" href="http://www.starflor.com" target="_blank"><img title="Starflor" src="/usr/media/gardens/home.photo.png" alt="Conservatory Garden by Starflor" width="163" height="130" /></a></div>\r\n</div>', '', '', 0.00, 0, '', '', '', 'gardens', 'conservatory-garden.jpg', '<A HREF="http://andrewprokos.com/photos/new-york/central-park/">Andrew Prokos</a>', '', '', 29, '/usr/media/gardens/gardens.css', '', 1, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 'Starbright Floral Design', 'Starbright Floral Design', 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00');
